# CLAUDE.md — annotated example

> This is a sanitized, annotated version of the conventions file I keep at the
> root of my projects (shown here in the shape I use for TechCoach AI).
> The annotations (blockquotes) explain why each section earns its place —
> every line exists because the agent got something wrong without it.

## Project

TechCoach AI — agentic learning platform. Next.js/TypeScript frontend,
API routes calling the Anthropic API, retrieval over Pinecone, deployed on
AWS ECS/Fargate.

> One paragraph of orientation. Without it, the agent guesses the stack from
> whatever file it opened first and plans accordingly.

## Commands

- Install: `npm install`
- Dev server: `npm run dev`
- Tests: `npm test` (run before proposing any commit)
- Typecheck: `npm run typecheck`
- Lint: `npm run lint`

> The agent will invent plausible-looking commands if you don't pin them.
> "Run tests before proposing a commit" turned flaky suggestions into a habit.

## Architecture map

- `app/` — Next.js routes and pages. UI only; no business logic here.
- `lib/retrieval/` — RAG pipeline: chunking, embedding, Pinecone queries.
- `lib/llm/` — Anthropic API calls, prompt templates, response parsing.
- `lib/db/` — persistence. All schema changes go through migrations.
- `infra/` — ECS/Fargate deployment config.

> A five-line map prevents the most expensive failure I hit early:
> confident refactors that moved logic to the wrong layer.

## Rules

1. **Never edit `infra/` without being explicitly asked.** Deployment config
   changes have burned me twice via "helpful" cleanup.
2. **No new dependencies without asking.** Propose the package and why first.
3. **All Anthropic API calls go through `lib/llm/client.ts`.** No inline
   fetch calls to the API anywhere else.
4. **Retrieval changes require a before/after on the eval set** in
   `lib/retrieval/evals/` — "it looks more relevant" is not evidence.
5. **Prefer editing existing files over creating new ones.** New-file sprawl
   is the agent's default; this line cut it dramatically.

> Rules are failure-derived, not aspirational. If a rule has never been
> violated, it probably doesn't need to be here.

## Style

- TypeScript strict; no `any` without a comment justifying it.
- Async/await over promise chains.
- Errors: throw typed errors from `lib/errors.ts`; no silent catches.

> Keep style short. Long style sections get ignored; linters enforce better.
